Tutorial 1 - Learn How Computers Communicate

6 steps

NOTE: Getting rewards from this quest is over as it was only applicable on the Earn app when it was part of a campaign. Therefore, submissions are not reviewed or are disabled. However, you are highly encouraged to still complete the quest to practice your understanding.

In today's interconnected world, it's crucial to understand how computers communicate. One key element of this communication is the use of APIs, or Application Programming Interfaces. APIs serve as a bridge between different software applications, allowing them to interact and share data. In this section, we will delve into the fascinating world of APIs, exploring how they work and why they are so integral to our digital lives.

In this tutorial, we will discuss APIs and then we will introduce you to an API we will be using to create a library for this campaign.

Learning Outcomes

By the end of this tutorial, you will be able to:

  • Understand the concept behind APIs
  • Learn what computers communicate with
  • Use cURL and Postman to explore APIs using HTTP and HTTPS

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 6

  • Step 1: The Application Programming Interface

    APIs are everywhere! Your smartphone, your laptop, and even your home devices have some sort of API to communicate between devices on the network or between hardware and software interfaces. You can think of APIs as a translation between two languages and also a specification of what it can do.

    Another good example is the most used technology today — the Internet. For example, if we are accessing the StackUp website, we are asking it to give us access as an HTTP request which contains data telling the server what to do.

    In this way, if our credentials are correct, the server of the website sends a response that we are now able to access the website. This is done through an API. The API can be any form of data. Maybe plain HTML content or even JSON.

    Libraries are also APIs

    When considered thoughtfully, libraries can indeed be seen as APIs - albeit more abstract and domain-specific than traditional application programming interfaces.

    If you import a library crate from Rust, you are basically bringing the available namespaces into your code from the library itself. This means you are also talking to the function definitions, the constants, the traits, the custom data types and custom interfaces written by whoever made that library!

    This way, communication between your code and their libraries are happening which is basically what APIs are. For example, if our library is used to communicate with a server’s API somewhere, it could look something like the diagram below

    You can really spot similarities from the first diagram. This is because your browser or application also uses some sort of API library to send HTTP or any protocol requests to the server! Mind blowing!

  • Step 2: Tips on Learning How An API Works

    Reading Documentation

    Do not underestimate the importance of reading and being a good reader. To become a good developer and engineer, you need to seek documentation. Tutorials are good but they do not give the full essence of the technology. You have to dive into the documentation itself.

    If something along the documentation is missing or the documentation itself is missing, you should open a ticket to the upstream project that documentation is needed. Although, cases do exist where documentation is sparse, especially old projects. If that is the case, you have to be ready to read the source code itself but it would be as time-consuming and more difficult.

    Reading Specifications

    Like the previous section, specifications are essentially just a more comprehensive form of documentation. A good example for this is the Quite Ok Image Format and the HTTP specification.

    Specifications are designed to focus more on “how to write an implementation to communicate with other implementations” rather than “how to communicate with the API”. Therefore, they are standards or protocols that APIs use.

  • Step 3: End of Life Date API

    In this campaign, we will be taking a look at https://endoflife.date, a site that aggregates information about release cycle dates and the end of life of products and software. This includes products such as smartphone brands and software such as Rust.

    Go and explore the site! Once you are done, we can begin exploring the API as well!

  • Step 4: Essential Tools to Explore Web APIs: cURL

    What is cURL?

    cURL is a command line utility that allows to transfer data from or to a server using URLs. It supports known protocols such as HTTP, HTTPS, and FTP. It is powered by the C library, libcurl, for all transfer-related features.

    How to install cURL

    Windows

    cURL is available on Windows. You can install it via a package manager such as scoop or Microsoft’s winget. Follow the instructions on how to install these package managers before installing cURL or just install it manually from the official site — https://curl.se/windows/.

    Mac and Linux

    cURL is usually installed by default on both Mac/OSX and Linux. However, if it is not installed, you can use a package manager like brew or your Linux distribution’s official package manager such as apt for Debian-based distributions and rpm for RPM-based distributions. Follow your systems’ guide on how to use and install from package managers as this will not be covered in this guide because of differences in distributions.

    Example Usage

    For our campaign, if you are going to use cURL to explore https://endoflife.date, you can simply just run the following set of commands:

    To get all release cycles of a specific product. Try replacing “yourproduct” with “rust”

    curl https://endoflife.date/api/yourproduct.json

    To get a specific release cycle of a specific product. Try replacing “yourproduct” with “rust” and “yourcycle” with “1.78”. To avoid confusion, cycles can also mean a product version.

    curl https://endoflife.date/api/yourproduct/yourcycle.json

    To get all products available for usage

    curl https://endoflife.date/api/all.json

    Although, running just curl alone is enough, future usage of curl might need you to be more specific. The long-hand command for our previous examples is

    curl --request GET --url <URL>

    where URL (without the “<” and “>” symbols) are the API endpoints. API endpoints are just the URL examples we used before. For now, you don’t need to know much about what other kinds of HTTP requests are. You just need to follow along for now.

    To prettify our output, you can use jq, a command line utility that filters json. Checkout the command from the screenshot below to see it in action.

    The API documentation is reused on this quest for clarity. See the documentation as reference — https://endoflife.date/docs/api.

  • Step 5: Essential Tools to Explore Web APIs: Postman

    If you prefer using a GUI for exploring API requests and responses instead of using cURL in your terminal, we can use Postman.

    So what is Postman? You can head to their website at https://www.postman.com/home and see

    Postman is an API platform for building and using APIs. Postman simplifies each step of the API lifecycle and streamlines collaboration so you can create better APIs—faster.
    - A description of what Postman is in their homepage.

    It’s a really powerful tool for this quest because it simplifies the way we explore APIs with the click of a button.

    Next, register an account for free at their website.

    To use Postman, see screenshot below for an example usage.

    You can also use their app by downloading it from their Download page. Follow the on-site instructions to install the app.

    The app looks like this on Linux (see screenshot below), it should look similar to your platform as well since it's an Electron app.

    Now let’s check it out for ourselves! Refer to the video below for a reference on how we can make use of Postman to make the same API call we did in the previous step.

    Because of how self-explanatory Postman is, the steps for exploring an API with Postman are:

    1. Click New
    2. Select HTTP as the protocol of API request
    3. Paste or type the API endpoints
    4. Click Send
    5. Check the Output
    6. Repeat from 3 or 1
